  "text": "Manufacturers commonly bundle or package options to reduce external variety. Rather than offering every option separately, they reduce the choice to predetermined sets of options. With this strategy, they directly address the key driver of external variety, the number of options offered. Option bundling does not affect internal or dynamic variety, although, according to [CITATION_1] , option bundling can reduce the buffers inside the manufacturing plant.",
